<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-10-22T11:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-10-22T11:36:00-05:00" n="1193" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1193">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5315.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Vera
                                    Cruz</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Vera Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-10-22T10:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 22, 1912—10 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Foreigners and noncombatants are between consulate and the <hi rend="italic">Des Moines</hi>, which lies 2,000 feet away. This zone
                            has been designated by myself and colleagues as neutral. Commanders on
                            both sides promise to respect and to protect it, being convinced that if
                            they do not Commander Hughes will, even if he has to land armed forces.
                            I have taken all possible steps to protect life and properties, even
                            established hospital in free zone, and have mounted messengers to be
                            able to act quickly when battle commences at 12 o’clock a.m., as
                            promised.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Canada.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>